HEADWORD: Eigne
<hw>Eigne</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[OF.
<ets>aisn⟦eacute⟧</ets>, <ets>ainsn⟦eacute⟧</ets>, F.
<ets>a⟦icir⟧n⟦eacute⟧</ets>, fr. L. <ets>ante natus</ets> born before.
Cf. <er>Esnecy</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>Eldest;
firstborn.</def> <rj><au>Blackstone.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Entailed; belonging to the eldest son.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Bastard eigne</b></col>, <cd>a bastard eldest son whose
parents afterwards intermarry.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

